<li>Kearns, Stephen, 2016. &ldquo;Bearing the Weight of
Reasons,&rdquo; in Lord &amp; Maguire (eds.) 2016: 173&ndash;190.</li>

<li>Kearns, Stephen, and Daniel Star, 2008. &ldquo;Reasons:
Explanations or Evidence,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 119:
31&ndash;56.</li>

<li>Keeling, Sophie, 2023. &ldquo;Controlling Our Reasons,&rdquo;
<em>No&ucirc;s</em>, 57: 832&ndash;849. doi:10.1111/nous.12431</li>

<li>Keller, Simon, 2013. <em>Partiality</em>, Princeton: Princeton
University Press.</li>

<li>Kiesewetter, Benjamin, 2018. &ldquo;Contrary-to-Duty Scenarios,
Deontic Dilemmas, and Transmission Principles,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>,
129: 98&ndash;115.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015. &ldquo;Instrumental Normativity: In
Defense of the Transmission Principle,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 125:
921&ndash;946.</li>

<li>Lechler, Andrea, 2012. &ldquo;Do Particularists Have a Coherent
Notion of a Reason for Action?&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 122:
763&ndash;772.</li>

<li>Li, Han, 2019. &ldquo;How Supererogation Can Save Intrapersonal
Permissivism,&rdquo; <em>American Philosophical Quarterly</em>, 56:
171&ndash;186.</li>

